    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the polar form of the following curves given in Cartesian form:

<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li><p>\(y^2=1+2x\)</p>
<p>\(r =\)[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
</li>

<li><p>\(2xy={@bb@}\)</p>
<p>\(r^2 =\)[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>
</li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>(a) We aim to find the polar form of \(y^2=1+2x\). We know that \(x=r\cos\theta\) and \(y=r\sin\theta\), so we can solve as follows:
\[
\begin{aligned}
y^2 &= 1+2x\\
(r\sin\theta)^2 &= 1 + 2r\cos\theta\\
r^2\sin^2\theta - 2r\cos\theta - 1 &= 0\\
&\text{using the quadratic formula}\\
r &= \frac{-(-2\cos\theta)\pm\sqrt{(-2\cos\theta)^2-4\sin^2\theta(-1)}}{2\sin^2\theta}\\
&= \frac{2\cos\theta \pm \sqrt{4 - 4\sin^2\theta + 4\sin^2\theta}}{2\sin^2\theta}\\
&= \frac{\cos\theta \pm 1}{\sin^2\theta}\\
&\text{as we know that } r \geq 0\\
&= \frac{\cos\theta+1}{\sin^2\theta}\\
&= \frac{\cos\theta+1}{1-\cos^2\theta}\\
&= \frac{1+\cos\theta}{(1-\cos\theta)(1+\cos\theta)} \\
&= \frac{1}{1-cos\theta}
\end{aligned}
\]
See below for a graph of this function:
